ducts such as Coca Cola, Worcestershire Sauce, and Palmolive Soap rely on African plants that were brought to the Americas on slave ships as provisions, medicines, cordage, and bedding. In this exciting, original, and groundbreaking book, Judith A. Carney and Richard Nicholas Rosomoff draw on archaeological records, oral histories, and the accounts of slave ship captains to show how slaves' food plots—"botanical gardens of the dispossessed"—became the incubators of African survival in the Americas and Africanized the foodways of plantation societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBlack peoplexEthnobotanyzAfricaxHistory. 0aBlack peoplexEthnobotanyzAmericaxHistory. 0aBlacksxEthnobotanyzAfricaxHistory. 0aBlacksxEthnobotanyzAmericaxHistory. 0aEnslaved personszAmericaxHistory. 0aEthnobotanyzAfricaxHistory. 0aEthnobotanyzAmericaxHistory. 0aMedicinal plantszAfricaxHistory. 0aMedicinal plantszAmericaxHistory. 0aPlants, EdiblezAfricaxHistory. 0aPlants, EdiblezAmericaxHistory. 0aSlaveszAmericaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Africa / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094953940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520949539423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520949539/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles